

母親を霜よけにして寝た子哉
With mother
as a shield from the frost
the child sleeps.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)


夜の雪だまつて通る人もあり
It is snowing tonight, and people 
silently 
walk by.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)


つくづくと雪山近く歩きけり
I walked beneath
the snowy mountains
in awe.
– Hoshino Tatsuko (1903-1984)


雪とけて　村一ぱいの　子どもかな
As the snow melts,
the town is flooded
with children.
— Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)


やれ打つな　はえが手をする　足をする
Stop, don’t swat!
Can’t you see the fly
begging for mercy?
— Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)


夏川を　こすうれしさよ　手にぞうり
Summer, river crossing;
such joy, sandals in hand.
— Yosa Buson (1716-1783)


露の玉百千万も葎かな
Beads of dew,
a multitude of them
resting upon the foliage.
-- Kawabata Bousha (1897-1941)


食べてゐる牛の口より蓼の花
Hanging from the mouth
of a grazing cow:
a knotweed flower.
-- Takano Sujuu (1893-1976)


手の前に蝶の息つぐ茸哉
Taking a break,
a butterfly rests 
on a nearby mushroom.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)


猫の子のくるくる舞やちる木のは
A kitten performs
its twirly and tumbling dance
among the falling leaves.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)


朝だちや　馬のかしらの　あまの川
Morning Departure
Horseback
Milky Way
— Meisetsu Naitou (1847-1926)


手にとらば消んなみだぞ あつき秋の霜
If I could gather them in my hands,
these inexorable tears:
a searing early frost.
– Matsuo Bashō (1644-1694)














